All permissions in the default scheme are group-based, so if the project lead is only in the "users" group then they get no special access to their own project.

This wastes time on first experimenting with a new JIRA instance (e.g. using the SDK) because it takes a while to work out that you can't even create issues in your own project because you don't have assign permission and can't leave it unassigned. 

The project lead should be able to do pretty much anything with their own project, even if they're not in the administrator or developer groups.

